<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / International Company News: Orix has visions of credit in
China
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER four decades of being judged for their political worthiness, Chinese
will now be assessed for their creditworthiness under a consumer finance
joint venture launched yesterday by Orix, the Japanese leasing company.
The Shanghai-based venture, claimed to be China's first consumer credit
company, will introduce consumers to instalment payments, which have
generally applied only to housing purchase schemes and Communist Party
members.
'We will be judging Chinese consumers in the same way that we judge the
creditworthiness of Japanese consumers. We are aiming at a managerial class,
people who can afford consumer durables,' Orix said yesterday. 'There hasn't
really been a system of giving credit ratings to people in China, so this an
historic thing.'
Credit has been slow to be accepted in China, which first created its own
plastic, the Great Wall debit card, seven years ago and has done business in
awkwardly large wads of renminbi or people's money, the Chinese currency.
Shanghai Yintong Trust, which opens next month, is a joint venture between
Orix and three Chinese partners: the Industrial and Commercial Bank of
China, the Shanghai Number One Department Store, and Shanghai Friendship
Overseas Chinese Company. Orix and the bank each hold 41.67 per cent of
Yin-Xin Credit, as the company is known in short, while the other two
Shanghai partners share the remaining ownership. Yin-Xin has a registered
capital of Dollars 2.1m and an initial contract life of 20 years.
The Japanese company has a long-term vision of Chinese customers borrowing
from Orix-linked loan shops and carrying a pocketful of credit cards, if the
Chinese government approves. The credit will be provided through state-owned
and foreign-backed stores and the sales agents of the Japanese consumer
electronics companies.
</TEXT>
