<TEXT>
After a year of advance Mr Grenville Dean, chairman of Merivale Moore, the
property company, felt able to give an upbeat message with the results for
the year to June 30.
'At the half year I was brave enough to indicate that the company was no
longer helplessly bleeding to death. I am pleased therefore to have some
good all-round news and progress to report, albeit not yet meriting the
ringing of bells.'
The shares rose 17p to 55p.
Net assets per share were 76.7p, against 77.3p a year earlier. Net debt was
cut from Pounds 49.3m to Pounds 29.6m, resulting in gearing of 283 per cent.
There was a pre-tax loss of Pounds 939,000, after an exceptional credit of
Pounds 2.36m relating to the settlement of a damages claim less exceptional
charges. The comparative loss was Pounds 23.6m, restated for FRS 3 and after
an exceptional charge of Pounds 19m.
Turnover was Pounds 24.3m (Pounds 30.3m). After a tax credit of Pounds 2.71m
(Pounds 1.14m) earnings per share were 12.9p (losses 164.5p).
Mr Dean thought the company had been able to achieve its initial objective
of rebuilding the balance sheet and now expected growth. Merivale had
started the present year in better financial health than the last and in a
'far more promising business climate'.
