<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / New classification for companies in FT-SE indices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A COMPREHENSIVE review of the companies and sectors which make up the FT-SE
Actuaries Share Indices has been undertaken for the first time since 1970.
As a result 303 companies have been reclassified and a number of new
economic groups, industry sectors and sub-sectors created.
The new system will take effect from January 4 next year, replacing two
existing classification methods, the FT-Actuaries and Stock Exchange
indices.
Mr Nicholas Fitzpatrick, a partner of Bacon &amp; Woodrow, the actuaries, who
chaired the classification committee for the new model, said the system was
universally accepted by fund managers.
He said it was intended to provide a service to investors by grouping
companies together in homogeneous industry sectors and sub-sectors.
Companies were informed of their new classifications by letter yesterday.
RTZ, Rank Organisation and Inchcape, three large companies thought to be
unhappy about the new sectors to which they have been assigned, each said
they were considering the implications of their moves.
The review takes account of the decline in the UK's industrial base, the
growth of service industries and the birth of a utilities group as a result
of the government's privatisation programme.
For the first time, the ground rules on which classification decisions are
made have been published. Companies are placed within sub-sectors on the
basis of the derivation of their published, audited profits. The rules say
'no changes in industry classification will be made on the basis of promises
of action or assertions by directors'.
Conglomerates have been defined as companies with at least three distinct
activities, none accounting for more than 50 per cent of profits, and each
contributing more than 10 per cent. Mr Fitzpatrick said the committee had
'at last found a way of getting BTR and Hanson in the same pot'.
All 2,375 listed and USM-quoted companies have been pigeonholed. Companies
have until October 31 to appeal if they feel mis-classified, and appeals
will be heard in November. After that changes will be considered quarterly.
Once the final list has been produced, histories of sector performance will
be back-dated to 1985.
The system has three tiers:
Seven economic groups, which replace the six existing groups. Out goes
'capital goods', which had been shrinking as a proportion of the total. New
groups include 'mineral extraction' and 'utilities';
40 instead of 35 sectors. Health and household and oil and gas, which had
become large sectors, are each divided into three. Others have been merged,
some have disappeared, and some been created: to be reviewed annually;
76 rather than 77 sub-sectors, with 18 new sub-sectors and 38 renamed
sub-sectors. Editorial comment, Page 19; New classifications, Page 42;
Companies affected, Page 23
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
