FT  08 OCT 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Amid a spate of programmes about the unsavoury world of the '90s teenager,
Public Eye: Teenage Kicks (BBC2, 8.00) examines the thriving drugs business
among young people. Parents and grandparents who wish to continue living in
cloud-cuckoo-land are strongly advised against watching.
At the start of the Michaelmas term, Class Action (C4, 8.00), the
educational magazine programme, looks at the response of Oxford University
to undergraduate suicides which although statistically on the low side,
causes concern.
Tomorrow's World (BBC 1, 7.30) includes a feature on Lewis in the Outer
Hebrides, now a place of windy peat bogs but in prehistoric times thickly
forested. Researchers at Edinburgh University investigate what might have
happened and whether the forests may yet be brought back.
Good, hammy fun with the late-night horror movie, The Beast With Five
Fingers (BBC1, 12.40) in which a deceased concert pianist's severed hand
gives spine-chilling performances.
