<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / Unions claim BT is targeting for redundancy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIONS representing workers at British Telecommunications yesterday claimed
the company was introducing a grading system which could be used to target
individuals for redundancy.
The points system draws upon individual's annual performance assessment,
their attendance records and whether or not disciplinary action has been
taken against them. Age was to have been a factor but this was dropped by BT
after complaints from the National Communications Union and the Society of
Telecom Executives.
BT, which employs 170,000, down from a peak of 250,000 in 1984, has been
shedding jobs for the past five years.
It now wants to make an audit of its staff in different operations as part
of an exercise to define the shape and skill-mix of its future organisation.
Staff in units that need to be slimmed down will be selected, on the basis
of the points system, either to remain in their jobs or to transfer to a
're-deployment unit'.
It will be staff at the bottom of the scale who will be transferred to the
redeployment unit and trained for other vacancies. At present there are 527
managers in this unit with 348 vacancies logged with it.
The NCU, the largest union within BT, said it was concerned that the
redeployment unit could be seen as a 'dumping ground' with individuals
within it vulnerable to being targeted for redundancy. It objected to people
being de-selected from their jobs on the basis of what it called 'an
arbitrary points system'.
BT said that people in the redeployment unit might be offered jobs they did
not want to take but they had a choice,as there was a voluntary redundancy
package.
BT, which at present is locked in talks with the NCU on the points system,
said it was committed to the goal of achieving planned reductions in jobs by
voluntary means.
The company, which wants to shed 15,000 jobs this year and a similar number
next year, said it could not make a categorical denial that there would
never be any compulsory redundancies. But it said: 'We are doing everything
we can to stick with volunteers for redundancy.'
Traditionally, British companies have chosen workers for enforced redundancy
on the principle that the shortest-serving employees go first.
Employers have grown increasingly unhappy with this system, mainly because
it gives managers little control over who goes. Considerable numbers in the
recession, including National Westminster Bank and Aston Martin, the luxury
carmaker, have turned to alternative methods - in particular selection
criteria which may draw upon performance, skills, versatility and
attendance.
Companies are well placed if they have performance appraisal systems in
place. Indeed, companies are frequently advised that an indirect benefit of
appraisal systems is that they can provide evidence of fairness in
redundancy selection.
</TEXT>
