<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / Charges dropped against West Midlands officers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THREE West Midlands police officers left the Old Bailey yesterday after
charges of perjury and conspiracy to pervert the course of justice in
connection with the prosecution of the Birmingham Six were dropped.
Mr Justice Garland ruled that a fair trial was no longer possible for the
three - Detective Constable Terence Woodwiss (left), retired Detective
Superintendent George Reade (centre) and Detective Sergeant Colin Morris.
The judge had heard lengthy legal arguments from their barristers that the
men could never receive a fair trial because of 'saturation' publicity since
the Birmingham Six were freed by the Appeal Court in March 1991.
The detectives had all denied the charges when they appeared in court on
Monday last week.
In a statement yesterday four of the Birmingham Six said: 'Today's decision
saddens and does not surprise us.'
</TEXT>
