<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / Dublin supports plea for public inquiry on Thorp
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE IRISH government has thrown its weight behind those calling for a public
inquiry to be held before the Thorp nuclear reprocessing plant at Sellafield
is granted revised authorisations for radioactive discharges.
In its second submission to the UK authorities, the Irish government says
there is 'no sound economic case' to be made for going ahead with the
project.
Mr Brian Cowen, Irish minister for transport and energy, yesterday said he
was publishing the submission due 'to the concerns and fears held in this
island regarding Sellafield'. He added: 'I wish to highlight and reinforce
with our European Community colleagues the Irish government's concerns and
misgivings regarding the British nuclear industry and the Sellafield plant
in particular.'
The report says: 'There are no demonstrable overall economic or security
benefits arising out of Thorp's operation which would justify it or balance
out possible and likely risks to public health and environmental damage. A
narrow base of benefits to BNFL (British Nuclear Fuels) or the UK economy
alone is not a sufficient justification.'
The Irish government says that 'important points of substance specifically
related to the draft discharge authorisations' made in its first submission
'had not been adequately addressed' by UK authorities.
The submission says 'the bringing on-stream of Thorp represents an
additional and unnecessary risk to the health and safety of the population'.
</TEXT>
