FT  08 OCT 93 / Receivers move into property company
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MONHOUSE, a London-based property company which owns Queens West, one of
Cardiff's best-known shopping centres, has gone into administrative
receivership.
Queens West, which was valued at Pounds 30m when it opened in Cardiff city
centre six years ago, has 70,000 sq ft of retail space on three floors and a
food theatre with seating for 430 people.
The centre's tenants include Laura Ashley, Currys, Burton and Dorothy
Perkins, but there are many vacant units. It is continuing to trade
normally.
Mr Mark Batten and Mr John Soden, of Price Waterhouse, have been appointed
joint administrative receivers. Mr Batten said yesterday that although
retailing in Cardiff had stood up well in the recession, Queens West had
suffered from not having quite as good a location as the rival St David's
Centre.
He said a number of options were being considered for the centre and, in the
meantime, it was business as usual. He added there would be a marketing
campaign to attract new shops.
