<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / Former Shell man jailed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FORMER engineer with Shell was jailed for 12 months at Southwark Crown
Court yesterday for accepting bribes to influence the award of a contract
for a floating accommodation vessel to be used in the North Sea.
Mr Francis Hemsworth, formerly a senior engineer with the oil company, had
pleaded guilty to two charges of corruptly accepting payments that totalled
more than Pounds 31,000.
The payments were made to him to influence the awarding of the contract for
the vessel to be used in Shell's Gannet oil field in the North Sea.
Mr John Napier, a former marketing manager, was also imprisoned for 12
months after pleading guilty to corruptly offering the bribes to Mr
Hemsworth.
Confiscation orders were also made against both men. Mr Hemsworth was
ordered to pay Pounds 31,000 and Mr Napier Pounds 25,467. Both men were also
ordered to pay part of the prosecution costs. Mr Hemsworth was ordered to
pay Pounds 6,500 and Mr Napier Pounds 13,500.
The convictions followed one of a series of investigations by the Serious
Fraud Office into corruption in the awarding of contracts in the North Sea
oil fields operated by both Shell and British Petroleum.
</TEXT>
