<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / Teachers oppose truancy tables
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE National Association of Head Teachers yesterday urged Mr John Patten,
the education secretary, to change his plans for publishing truancy league
tables for schools next month.
Mr David Hart, the association's general secretary, described the proposed
tables as 'dangerously false' because they would be based on how many pupils
had missed at least one half-day of school, rather than on the total amount
of days missed through truancy.
He said the former figure would produce 'such extreme variations in the
published data as to make it meaningless'.
Mr Hart added that many truancies lasting for only a half-day were
parentally condoned, and that this could distort the figures for school
comparisons, leaving 'a very real prospect of government policy in this area
being exposed to ridicule'.
Mrs Ann Taylor, shadow education secretary, said the association's
complaints, made in a letter to Mr Patten, provided 'alarming evidence of
the consequences of government by gimmick'.
