<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / The Conservative Party Conference: Mortgage tax relief
system on Budget agenda
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government is reviewing the system of mortgage tax relief, but no
decisions have been taken and it wants to avoid steps that would deliver a
shock to the housing market.
The Treasury has put a further reduction of tax relief on mortgage interest
payments on its list of possible revenue-raising measures in the November 30
Budget. But it is understood that detailed discussions of the taxation side
of the Budget have yet to begin.
Asked about his plans for mortgage tax relief yesterday, Mr Kenneth Clarke,
the chancellor, said only that he was looking 'at all possible options in
taxation' and that his Budget was not yet finalised.
Close associates of Mr John Major, the prime minister, said yesterday that
he would be very reluctant to accept any move that would be perceived as a
break of the Tory general election manifesto promise to 'maintain' mortgage
interest relief.
They indicated that the government would therefore be unlikely to take such
a radical step as abolishing relief for new home buyers from April 1995 as
reported in yesterday's Guardian newspaper. However, it is also clear that
mortgage tax relief is no longer a sacred cow for the Conservative party.
Relief is due to be pared from April as part of staged tax increases
announced in the March Budget. From 1994-95 relief will be granted at the
lowest 20 per cent rate of income tax on interest paid up to the Pounds
30,000 ceiling for mortgages, compared with 25 per cent at present.
Treasury ministers are keen to see a further erosion in mortgage interest
relief which represents a substantial cost to the exchequer and is regarded
as a factor which distorts the British housing market.
Mortgage interest relief cost the government Pounds 5.2bn in 1992-93. But
this burden has fallen in line with lower interest rates so the cost in
1993-94 is estimated at Pounds 4.3bn. The Treasury estimates that it will
cost Pounds 3.6bn next year.
The low interest rates - with mortgage rates about half the level of the
early 1990s - should help ease political resistance to any move cutting
mortgage interest relief in the Budget. Homeowners are substantially better
off than a year ago, while tax relief on a Pounds 30,000 mortgage is now
worth only about Pounds 600 a year.
However, the housing market is still fragile and lagging the economic
recovery. In view of this ministers are approaching the issue cautiously.
</TEXT>
