<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / The Conservative Party Conference: Plans set to simplify NHS
management structure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS TO reshape the central management structure of the National Health
Service will be announced by Mrs Virginia Bottomley, health secretary, next
month.
A simplification of the higher levels of NHS management could lead to
substantial job losses in regional health authorities and the service's
Leeds-based management executive.
Mrs Bottomley told the Conservative conference yesterday that her proposals
would reduce the number of health authorities. 'They will both simplify and
clarify structures, and provide more resources for patient care.'
Since the summer ministers have been considering the report of the functions
and manpower review, a committee set up to look at the service's
higher-level management needs following the market-based 1991 NHS reforms.
The committee's report presented a range of options. But ministers appear to
favour reducing the 14 English regional health authorities to about eight.
These would be amalgamated with regional outposts of the management
executive which have, since 1991, liaised with trust hospitals. A subsequent
stage of the restructuring exercise could lead to the abolition of regional
authorities as separate statutory bodies.
Slimming down the central management structure would offer Mrs Bottomley the
immediate advantage of being able to divert funds into clinical services at
a time of severe public spending constraints.
Supporters of the market-based philosophy behind the NHS reforms believe a
smaller central structure would increase the freedom of trust hospitals and
district purchasing authorities. But the abolition of regional authorities
would be challenged by campaigners for greater democratic accountability in
the NHS. Regional authorities' non-executive members, while not elected, are
chosen to reflect community interests.
Mrs Bottomley announced yesterday that a further 99 NHS trusts will become
operational next April, bringing to 389 the number of hospitals, community
and ambulance services run directly by their local managements. By April,
trusts will be responsible for more than 90 per cent of hospital and
community health service revenue. Mrs Bottomley will make decisions on a
further 44 trust applications later this year.
Mrs Bottomley said trust status - which removes hospitals from the control
of district health authorities - had benefited patients.
Waiting times had been reduced, and 116 patients were being treated compared
to 100 before the switch to trust status.
Dr Sandy Macara, chairman of the British Medical Association council, said
the health secretary had recognised in her conference speech that there had
been a substantial increase in NHS productivity, but this had not been
matched by the necessary increase in resources.
</TEXT>
