FT  08 OCT 93 / The Conservative Party Conference: 'Green' VAT move defended
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE imposition of value added tax on domestic fuel and power would help
towards a 'cleaner, greener world', Mr Tim Yeo, environment minister, said
yesterday.
He told a fringe meeting in Blackpool: 'We as Conservatives are committed to
putting our money where our pollution is. If we pollute, we pay.'
He told the Tory Green Initiative meeting: 'We are harnessing the market to
create a greener, cleaner Britain and a cleaner, greener world.
'That's why we as a party must throw our full might behind the Budget
decision to extend VAT to domestic fuel.'
He added: 'The fact is that nearly all of us spend too much on heating our
homes.'
The heating bill for a three-bedroomed semi-detached house was more than
Pounds 500 a year, he said. But a modern energy-efficient house with full
insulation and modern boiler could be heated for Pounds 150.
He confirmed the government's commitment to using market instruments, such
as tradeable permits, to meet environmental goals.
He said the Department of the Environment was considering introducing such
permits, which control the amount of a pollutant that is allowed to be
discharged, for sulphur dioxide emissions.
'The principle here is that if the emissions from your factory are lower
than they might otherwise be, you have surplus pollution permits which you
can sell to some other factory who are exceeding their allowances,' he said.
'Your company makes money out of your environmental awareness, the other guy
pays - in cash - for his environmental profligacy.'
Among other similar initiatives, Mr Yeo said the government was also
investigating incentive charges to control water pollution and charges for
water abstraction.
On waste disposal, he said the introduction of a landfill levy would
'increase the cost of this method of waste disposal and thus increase the
financial attractions of more environmentally desirable alternatives'.
He added: 'Producer responsibility would give a further and substantial
boost to recycling by giving packaging producers and fillers (including
retailers) an incentive to reduce packaging waste and recycle it wherever
practicable.'
</TEXT>
