FT  08 OCT 93 / The Conservative Party Conference: Portillo attacks
rightwing tax stance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL Portillo, chief secretary to the Treasury, last night identified
the restoration of 'sound finance' as the prerequisite for a revival in the
government's fortunes, Philip Stephens writes.
Taking a further step towards establishing his credentials as the true
inheritor of Lady Thatcher's mantle, he launched a thinly veiled attack on
the Tory right campaigning against tax increases.
He told a fringe meeting hosted by the Conservative Political Centre that
Lady Thatcher had made lower public borrowing the first priority of her
governments: 'The restoration of sound public finance overrode all other
ambitions even when in 1981 we were forced to raise taxes against our deeper
instincts.'
He added: 'If a government believe that a policy is right for the country,
then it must pursue it, even if it leads to unpopularity.'
Mr Portillo combined his call for fiscal responsibility with an equally
strong call for the government to stick with policies designed to squeeze
public spending and to give individuals more control over their own lives.
