<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / The Conservative Party Conference: Protection pledge for
state sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DOUGLAS HURD, the foreign secretary, last night fired a warning shot at
those of the Tory right seeking to further reduce the role of the state.
Taking a sideswipe at supporters of 'permanent revolution' he stressed the
government's commitment to respect as well to reform the public sector.
His comments were reinforced by a re-affirmation by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the
chancellor, that the government's overall strategy should be based on an
'American approach to free-market economics and a European approach to
welfare'.
In a speech which followed a series of attacks from right-wing ministers and
Tory activists on the public sector, Mr Hurd said the party should not give
the impression that we 'believe in a permanent cultural revolution, in the
style of Trotsky of chairman Mao'.
His comments, carefully prepared after close consultation with colleagues,
were seen as a signal that the centrist majority in Mr John Major's cabinet,
is unwilling to surrender the public services agenda.
Mr Hurd told the Tory Reform Group: 'We do not want to break the mould of
every public service afresh in every Parliament. We must show that we are
not driven by ideology to question every function of the state, to make
impossible the life of our public servants, or to depreciate the worth and
quality of the different public services.'
He defended strongly the need to overhaul key public services like
education, the health service and prison system to ensure that they
functioned more like a sophisticated and responsive market.
But he coupled that with a warning that the policies of the Thatcher era did
not fit the priorities of the 1990s: 'We spent much of the 1980s cutting
back on the overblown responsibilities of the state. Our task now is to
strike the right balance in working out the role of the state in the 1990s.'
The government's commitment to deregulate and to introduce market
disciplines in the public sector should not be mistaken for a 'vendetta
against the state in the areas of national life where its role must remain
central'.
That sentiment was echoed by Mr Clarke who told reporters that the prospect
of public spending cuts should not be taken as an attack on the basic
principles of the welfare state.
</TEXT>
