<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / The Conservative Party Conference: Bottomley announces new
round of trust hospitals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MRS Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, announced yesterday that a
further 99 hospitals and other medical establishments would be given
self-governing trust status in April.
She also promised to expand the number of family doctors authorised to
control their budgets, and forecast administrative savings through a
reduction in the number of health authorities.
Details of the administrative changes - expected to make the most impact on
regional health authorities - would be announced to parliament.
Mrs Bottomley said trust status - which removed hospitals from the control
of district health authorities - had benefited patients.
Waiting times had been reduced, and 116 patients were being treated compared
to 100 before the switch to trust status.
She said: 'In two years' time virtually every hospital, community and
ambulance service will have become a trust'.
Scoffing at abolition threats made by Mr David Blunkett, Labour's shadow
health secretary, she maintained that trusts were good for staff, good for
patients and were 'here for good'.
Mrs Bottomley undertook to apply the same determination in extending the
number of 'budget-holding' family doctors, whose skills 'make our money go
further for patients'.
She contended that Labour MPs loathed fundholding - 'they level down,' she
said. 'We level up.'
Emphasising the importance of avoiding waste in the NHS which spent Pounds
100m every day, she said the saving of one penny in the pound meant an extra
Pounds 1m every day for patients.
</TEXT>
