<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / Names back corporate membership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ONE OF the biggest organisations of Lloyd's Names
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
the individuals whose assets support the insurance market - is to recommend
its members vote in favour of the market's plans to admit corporate members
at an extraordinary general meeting later this month.
The decision of the Association of Lloyd's Members, which represents up to
9,000 Names, will boost confidence at the market where there are hopes that
as much as Pounds 1bn in corporate capital will back Lloyd's syndicates next
year.
However Lloyd's still faces potential opposition from a second group
representing Names involved in legal action. Mr Christopher Stockwell,
chairman of the Lloyd's Names Associations Working Party said he would
reserve judgment until 18 October, two days before the EGM.
Mr Neil Shaw, the association chairman, said its committee had studied an
independent report which showed Names would not be disadvantaged by the
entry of new corporate investors. The association and the working party
commissioned the report. It is understood the advisers, who have not been
named, are a leading firm of actuarial consultants.
'In their overall opinion the proposals will be beneficial to Lloyd's and
all of its members and may even be necessary for the future prosperity of
the society,' said the association.
Mr Shaw said it was 'satisfied' with assurances given by Mr Peter Middleton,
Lloyd's chief executive, that Names will be able to maintain their market
involvement at 1993 levels. Although Names have been hard-hit by losses of
more than Pounds 6bn in the last five years, many are now anxious to
continue trading in view of insurance rate rises and improved prospects for
profits.
Lloyd's is aiming to make an out-of-court offer to Names taking legal action
to recover losses before the end of the year. The association said they had
been told by Mr Middleton that if a settlement is reached, arrangements will
be made for them to resume underwriting.
The association has also advised its members not to delegate responsibility
for voting at the EGM but the working party wants proxy votes to allow it to
press for better settlement terms.
</TEXT>
