<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / Loopholes let pirates through legal net
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SATELLITE television channels
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
particularly subscription movie and sports channels - are turning into
billion-pound businesses in Europe, but there is little specific legislation
to protect them against increasingly sophisticated pirates.
The Motion Picture Export Association of America, the Hollywood trade
association, said that only the UK, Sweden and France had passed laws to ban
unauthorised decoders and smart cards which 'unlock' the scrambled signal.
Mr George Eriksson, deputy director of the association in Europe, said he
planned to lobby the European Commission to get a ban on unauthorised
decoders throughout the community.
BSkyB has only bought the pay-television rights for the UK. Making sure that
the signal is secure is part of BSkyB's contractual obligations under
agreements with the studios.
The UK government has dealt with the issue by inserting a section in the
Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1988. This created a criminal offence
with a fine of up to Pounds 5,000.
The new section says that 'a person who makes, imports, sells or lets for
hire any un-authorised decoder shall be guilty of an offence'. It is
apparently not an offence to use a pirate decoder.
The legislation adds that it would be a defence for the defendant to prove
'that he did not know, and had no reasonable grounds for knowing that the
decoder was an unauthorised decoder'.
</TEXT>
