<DATE>931008
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / Irish satellite bandits enjoy roaring trade: BSkyB downplays
decoders - EC urged to impose a ban / Smart card fights microchips
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE, RICHARD DONKIN and RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BALLYEGAN is a hamlet in County Offaly in Ireland's agricultural heartland
so small that it does not even have a sub-post office.
Apart from the tractors on the lanes and cows grazing in the fields, the
only sign of economic activity is the local pub, 0'Meara's Black Bull -
except, that is, for a two-storey house called The Lodge.
The house is an important staging post for unauthorised decoders that
unscramble the satellite channels of British Sky Broadcasting, the satellite
television network in which Pearson, owner of the Financial Times, has a
significant stake. The decoders are not just supplying the Irish market but
are now being exported in large numbers to the UK.
Advertisements placed by the Ballyegan company in Ireland promise smart
cards to decode all the BSkyB channels which normally cost subscribers
Pounds 19.99 a month.
'Save hundreds of pounds in fees you have to pay each month,' says the
advertisement, which also adds: 'Agents wanted for all parts of Eire.'
Mr Jack Malloy who lives at The Lodge said he helped out with the business
of distributing the cards. His niece, he added, was married to Mr David
Lyons, who runs the UK arm of the business.
The company that placed the advertisement is registered in Dublin and called
Satellite Decoding Systems. It has a UK branch in a semi-detached house in
Dingle Avenue, Appleton, near Warrington in Cheshire. Advertisements have
also been placed in Cheshire offering to decode all the BSkyB channels.
The company charges Pounds 220 for a card to unscramble the BSkyB channels -
not, on the surface, a good deal. All 18 channels including three film
channels and Sky Sports can be legitimately obtained for Pounds 240 a year.
But the pirate card promises to work forever.
The company says its service is almost a parallel subscription service - if
BSkyB changes its codes or sends out new official cards, Satellite Decoding
Systems offers to provide a new card for Pounds 30.
Mr Lyons, a tall Irishman, answered the door at his Warrington home
yesterday and denied that he was doing anything illegal.
'The only thing we are doing in this country is advertising,' he said. 'If I
thought we were doing anything to damage Sky TV to the point where it was
unacceptable we would pack it in,' he added.
He said his solicitors had been instructed to fight a writ from BSkyB at the
beginning of the month issuing a restraining order against his company for
breaking UK copyright laws.
Mr Lyons said he had written to BSkyB about his system. He said: 'They know
about us. I don't suppose they are very enthralled about it all.'
Mr Gary Davey, deputy managing director of BSkyB, was dismissive yesterday
about the activities of the pirates.
'You find one that works? People have been trying to crack the system since
its first month,' said Mr Davey, who conceded that a number of serious
attempts had been made by pirates.
'At least once a month there is an attempt,' he added.
The company monitors the pirates closely, Mr Davey said, and sometimes lets
them spend a lot of money on a system before changing the codes or the
information sent over the satellite to decoder boxes in individual homes.
'Then they lose their shirts,' Mr Davey said.
'Our system has been cracked. But we control it over the air. It can't be
permanently cracked,' he added, claiming that the information sent over the
satellite could be changed 50 times a second.
It is not an argument that much impresses Mr Lyons who was yesterday
demonstrating one of his cards in Ireland. He declined to demonstrate his
system in the UK, he said for legal reasons.
He said of BSkyB: 'They tried to turn our cards off a month ago and
succeeded in putting out of action 10 per cent of their own cards. Their
switchboards were jammed. All the satellite operators across Europe have had
their codes cracked. Nobody has produced a foolproof system.'
Mr Lyons said the cards were being mailed over to the UK from Ireland then
remailed in the UK by an assistant who did not know the contents of the
packages. He claimed this device would escape the restrictions on importing
unauthorised decoders.
Cheshire Trading Standards department is taking an interest in the
activities of Satellite Decoding Systems and may take action although the
department has not had any complaints from customers of the company.
According to a woman answering telephone inquiries at the Warrington
address, the company is swamped with applications. 'We have sold 2,000 cards
in the past six weeks,' she said.
The Ballyegan-Warrington connection looks like a tiny part of the growing
trade in unauthorised decoders. Satellite magazines all over Europe carry
advertisements for the unauthorised cards.
The Ballyegan company says it acts as an agent for a supplier based in
Bochum in Germany.
Mega-Sat in Bochum advertises in a German trade magazine called Infosat and
offers not just cards to crack BSkyB but also the film service of FilmNet
which operates in the Low Countries. Industry specialists on piracy believe
Mega-Sat is an important source of the unauthorised cards.
BSkyB only buys the UK rights to the movies it shows and although the
channels are distributed on the Astra satellite all over Europe they should
not be legitimately available there. In the UK the potential problem for
BSkyB is loss of revenue.
In Ireland, satellite dealers make it clear that pirate decoders are
available in the marketplace and are already big business.
Mr Paul McKenna of Electroplus, a satellite specialist in Dublin, said
yesterday that BSkyB's VideoCrypt system was 'a relatively simple code and
can be broken easily'.
Mr McKenna said that a week ago BSkyB had changed its signal to render the
pirate cards useless. 'Within two or three days the pirate cards were
replaced with new ones,' he said.
He added that the pirates had significant financial backing and said that
specialists from San Francisco had been involved.
A UK television executive who asked not to be named said yesterday that he
had pirate cards which had been decoding BSkyB channels for the past six
months.
However, he added that BSkyB had successfully damaged the picture last week
and now the picture slipped in and out of its scrambled form every two to
three seconds and was virtually unwatchable. He has not tried to get a
replacement card.
When VideoCrypt was first introduced, BSkyB executives said it was a system
that could not be beaten, mainly because a new card could be sent out every
three months if the codes were cracked.
One senior BSkyB director said yesterday that they could send out a new card
every week if necessary.
In fact BSkyB viewers are being signed up on 12-month contracts and it seems
that one card is meant to last throughout that time.
That is perhaps an indication of the confidence of BSkyB that the pirates
can be held at bay - or a measure of the complacency of the satellite
venture.
</TEXT>
