<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / Barclays taxation hearing opposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Clinton administration has urged the US Supreme Court not to hear an
appeal from Barclays Bank of the UK against California's unitary taxation
system.
Mr Drew Days, solicitor general, argued in a brief filed yesterday there was
no longer any need for the court to review the case since California had
already changed its tax law to meet the objections raised by Barclays and
other foreign companies.
If the Supreme Court takes the administration's advice - which reverses the
position of the Reagan and Bush administrations - it would leave standing a
decision by the California supreme court in favour of the state and against
Barclays.
Although the UK bank's appeal specifically involves a Dollars 150,000 tax
bill from 1977, the accumulation of interest on this and similar cases
brought by other foreign companies means a total of Dollars 900m is at stake
for California. Cases involving US-based multinationals cover a further
Dollars 3.1bn in disputed tax assessments.
Mr Brad Sherman, a member of the California Franchise Tax Board, the state
body involved in the Barclays case, hailed the solicitor general's brief as
'a much-needed economic boost for California' and said it 'virtually assured
a victory for California over the multinational corporations'.
Barclays argues that California's system of unitary assessment is
unconstitutional, because it conflicts with the norms of international
taxation and so interferes with the federal government's sole right to
regulate foreign commerce.
Under the unitary taxation method California assesses taxes on a proportion
of a company's worldwide income, rather than on income earned in the state.
Barclays and the UK government will file briefs next week, and a Supreme
Court decision on whether to hear the case is expected at the beginning of
November.
</TEXT>
