<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / More troops for Somalia: US will not cut and run from its
mission, pledges Clinton
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton, declaring that 'we must finish the work we set out
to do', last night ordered the doubling of the US military presence in
Somalia but promised that all but a few hundred non-combatant personnel
would be home by March 31 next year.
In a sober televised address from the Oval Office, which sought to define US
policy, he insisted the US could not 'cut and run' and leave Somalia to the
starvation and anarchy which prevailed before the US intervention last
November.
'We need more strength to do our job,' Mr Clinton declared. To this end an
additional 1,700 infantry troops and 104 armoured vehicles were being
despatched immediately along with 3,600 Marines to be stationed offshore on
an aircraft carrier and in two amphibious groups.
Their mission, he said, would be to protect the 4,700 US troops already in
Somalia, to keep open roads and airfields so that humanitarian supplies
could still get through, to maintain pressure on those fighting US and UN
forces and to give the Somalis time to achieve their own political
solutions.
In pursuit of the last goal he was sending Mr Robert Oakley, US envoy under
President George Bush and at the beginning of the current administration,
back to Somalia with the brief to facilitate negotiations.
Mr Clinton did not mention by name General Mohammed Farah Aideed, the
faction leader, whose forces killed 13 Americans in a bloody confrontation
last weekend and another in Mogadishu yesterday. He said it was vital not to
personalise any conflict.
But he said that if the US pulled out forthwith, as some in Congress have
demanded, 'aggressive thugs and terrorists would conclude the best way to
change our policy was to kill our people'.
The president said he was stepping up efforts to persuade other nations,
including those in the region, to send in forces to replace Americans.
Private US contractors would be invited to take over the logistical work
undertaken by US troops.
Repeatedly Mr Clinton emphasised that a political solution could only be
reached by the Somalis themselves. He argued that until last June the US
mission was clearly achieving success and that, although perhaps 1m Somalis
still depended on relief supplies, there was plenty of evidence of life
returning to normal outside Mogadishu, the capital.
In the morning the president had held what was described by some as a
'spirited' session with leaders of both parties in congress.
In spite of much criticism then vented, Mr Clinton at least had the
satisfaction after his address of hearing Senator Bob Dole, the Republican
leader, commend both his actions and his explanations.
He also met a criticism from Mr Dole by stating that US troops in Somalia
would be operating under American, not UN, command and control.
Compounding problems for the administration is a post-mortem over why last
weekend's raid on the forces of Gen Aideed went so badly wrong.
</TEXT>
