<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / Ukraine nuclear pact threatened
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JILL BARSHAY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UKRAINE and Russia are at odds over the terms of their agreement last month
for the transfer of strategic nuclear weapons on Ukrainian soil to Russia.
The viability of the accord reached at a summit meeting in Massandra in the
Crimea is now in doubt.
Russia has accused Ukraine of fraudulently changing the wording of the
agreement to exclude 46 modern SS-24 missiles from removal to Russian
territory. Two weeks ago Moscow quietly announced that it considered the
transfer agreement null and void.
Ukraine has responded by saying that Russia misled Ukraine during the
signing of documents by setting down a text that was not what Ukraine had
negotiated. Ukraine insists its changes were made in the presence of Mr
Viktor Chernomyrdin, Russian prime minister, before he signed.
The penned-in changes are not initialled in the margin as is customary
diplomatic practice. Ukraine sticks to its interpretation that all nuclear
weapons are not covered under the protocol. It says it is ready to
renegotiate but has set a list of conditions before any pact can be
implemented. These include compensation for the short-range tactical nuclear
weapons it voluntarily transferred to Russia in May 1992.
There is currently no timetable for reopening nuclear talks between the two
sides. Nor is there a timetable for the Ukrainian parliament to ratify the
1991 Start 1 nuclear arms reduction treaty signed between the US and the
Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
