<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 93 / Council of Europe admits Romania
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD MORTIMER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VIENNA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ROMANIA yesterday became the 32nd member state of the Council of Europe, in
a brief ceremony in Vienna where a two-day summit of the organisation begins
today.
Mr Teodor Melescanu, the Romanian foreign minister, fulfilled the main
condition of membership by signing the European Convention on Human Rights
on behalf of his country. This document is, in the words of Mrs Catherine
Lalumiere, the Council's secretary-general, 'the ideological foundation of
our organisation'.
Romania's membership was approved by the Council's parliamentary assembly
and committee of ministers only last week. It had been controversial because
of doubts about the country's human rights record and particularly its
treatment of Hungarian and gipsy ethnic minorities.
Welcoming the new member to 'the European family', Mrs Lalumiere said
pointedly that she was 'thinking of all the Romanians, whatever their
origin', and that Romania was joining an organisation 'which had a duty to
remain vigilant'.
Representatives from other east European countries not yet admitted to the
Council, including Russia, will attend a pre-Summit 'exchange of view', with
the leaders of the member countries in Vienna this morning.
</TEXT>
