<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow hesitant as jobs report
is awaited
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
PROGRAM buying and strong financial stocks helped US share prices post
modest gains across the board yesterday, but afternoon selling brought
prices back down from their new highs, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 11.73 at 3,598.99,
short of its high for the day of 3,605.98. The more broadly based Standard &amp;
Poor's 500 finished 0.46 lower at 460.74, while the Amex composite ended up
1.68 at 463.36, and the Nasdaq composite 2.50 higher at 764.77, close to a
new record.
Trading volume on the NYSE was 276m shares, and rises outnumbered declines
by 1,105 to 858.
Prices opened only slightly firmer, as traders and investors waited for a
lead from the bond market. Although bond prices rose marginally in early
trading, they failed to provide much impetus to equity prices. Participants
in both markets seemed reluctant to trade actively ahead of tomorrow's
important September employment report.
Additionally, equity investors remained nervous about the approaching third
quarter reporting season. Some are worried that the moderate rate of
economic growth recorded over the summer will have hindered corporate
profitability, and that third quarter earnings will come in below
expectations.
Stocks, however, picked up ground later in the morning, aided by sporadic
computerised buy programs and firmer financial stocks, before easing back
from their peaks in the afternoon. Among financials, banks were mostly
higher in the wake of an announcement from Chemical Banking that it would
report record net income for the third quarter. Chemical rose Dollars  1/4
to Dollars 45 3/8 , Citicorp added Dollars  3/8 at Dollars 38 7/8 , Chase
Manhattan put on Dollars  1/8 at Dollars 37 1/2 , NationsBank firmed Dollars
 1/8 to Dollars 53 and BankAmerica rose Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 44 1/4 .
Semiconductor stocks, hit hard on Tuesday by poor earnings from Advanced
Micro Devices, rebounded in early trading, but suffered in a late sell-off.
Texas Instruments ended down Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 69 7/8 , Motorola
finished unchanged at Dollars 98 1/2 and Intel, traded on the Nasdaq market,
fell Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 69 1/4 . Advanced Micro itself remained under
heavy selling pressure, falling another Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 21 in volume
of 4m shares.
Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber rose Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 46 1/2 after the
company said that it expects to report third quarter net income of between
Dollars 130m and Dollars 135m, up from Dollars 91m a year ago.
Nike fell Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 45 1/8 on the news that Michael Jordan,
the basketball star and the most famous promoter of Nike goods, is to
retire.
Canada
TORONTO prices posted strong gains in moderate trading, led by surging gold
issues. The TSE-300 composite index rose 41.37 points, or 1.03 per cent to
close at 4,055.48, according to preliminary data. Advancing issues
outnumbered declines 444 to 281.
The gold group jumped 4.1 per cent as the price of gold in New York rose.
Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce said it expects fiscal 1994 loan losses
to decline slightly from the forecast fiscal 1993 level of CDollars 920m. It
rose  3/8 to 30 5/8.
</TEXT>
