<DATE>931007
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 93 / Bank of Scotland surges despite weak demand
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HIGHER loan margins and increased fees helped Bank of Scotland raise interim
pre-tax profits 58 per cent to Pounds 117.6m, against Pounds 74.2m, despite
being hampered by weak loan demand.
Economic recovery enabled provisions for bad debts to be lowered 25 per cent
compared with the second half of last year to Pounds 174.4m in the six
months to August 31. But this was still 26 per cent up on the first half of
last year.
Assets such as loans rose only 1 per cent on the second half of last year to
Pounds 29.4bn, well within the bank's self-imposed limit of 5 per cent asset
growth for the year.
Mr Bruce Pattullo, governor and chief executive, had been surprised by the
'extremely weak' loan demand. As a result, assets might well expand this
year by less than the 5 per cent limit it had set in order to maintain its
capital adequacy ratio. He said improvements in management and the reshaping
of the bank over the past three years had started 'to come through to the
bottom line'.
Bad debt provisions should continue to fall in the second half. This would
be helped by some release of provisions as it sold assets such as distressed
companies which it had helped to continue trading.
Operating profits before bad debt provisions rose 39 per cent to Pounds
288.2m. Net interest income rose 22 per cent to Pounds 376.1m (Pounds
307.3m) and non-interest income rose 24 per cent rise to Pounds 186.5m
(Pounds 150m).
The rise in net interest income was achieved by increasing the average
margin on loans from 2.37 per cent to 2.57 per cent. This was reflected in a
widening of the spread between interest charged on assets and paid on
liabilities.
Mr Pattullo said that margins on syndicated loans to large corporate
customers were starting to narrow as competition re-emerged, but this had
been more than offset by the rise in margins on loans to small business
customers.
More than half the rise in fee and income commission in the clearing bank
came through branches and included increases in personal and corporate
customer charges. Mr Pattullo expected further improvements in the second
half.
The Bank of Wales subsidiary, which suffered a Pounds 15.3m loss last year
because of problems with a finance subsidiary, returned to a half-year
profit of Pounds 400,000.
The bank reduced its ratio of costs to income to 49.6 per cent, in spite of
a 10 per cent rise in expenses to Pounds 274.4m. It raised its interim
dividend 5.6 per cent to 1.87p, against 1.77p. It maintained its tier 1
ratio of core capital to assets at 5.8 per cent after retaining Pounds 40.4m
profit. The shares closed 3.5p up at 184p.
Lex, Page 24
</TEXT>
