<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 93 / Clinton may send 2,000 more troops to Somalia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN and MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton is considering sending up to 2,000 more US troops to
Somalia and may set a date for the withdrawal of all US forces from the
country.
The possible developments, including sending as many as another 50 armoured
vehicles, were revealed by administration officials last night. They suggest
Mr Clinton has decided to escalate attacks on the forces of General Mohammed
Farah Aideed, the Somali faction leader, prior to a withdrawal.
No details were immediately forthcoming, but earlier, in brief but carefully
worded remarks, the president had insisted it was essential the US conclude
its military mission in Somalia but that it do so 'honourably' and without
leaving behind 'a reversion to the absolute chaos and terrible misery that
existed before'.
In the US view, Gen Aideed is culpable on two main counts - for the killing
of 12 US servicemen last weekend and the desecration of their bodies,
graphically captured on TV pictures, and for the threat he poses to the US
and UN humanitarian and peacekeeping missions.
Mr Clinton said he would confer today with leaders of both parties in
Congress. An address to the nation at a later date was also planned, he
said. The president has been forced to set aside for the moment his domestic
policy agenda in the face of political and public pressure for clear-cut
action in Somalia.
Earlier, a possible confrontation with Congress was averted when the Senate
agreed to postpone by at least a week a vote that could have led to a
cut-off in funds for the operation.
Senator George Mitchell, the majority leader, made it clear the delay was
designed to give the president more time to formulate policy and to allow
congressional emotions, inflamed by the grisly TV pictures of dead US
servicemen in Mogadishu, to cool down. In fact, the congressional debate,
while frequently critical of the administration, has also cut across party
lines. Yesterday a letter signed by 65 Republican congressmen demanded an
early withdrawal, but Senator Robert Dole, the Republican minority leader,
argued that 'this is not a time for panic'.
Democrats were similarly divided. Senator Paul Simon of Illinois, while
criticising the administration's fixation with getting rid of Gen Aideed,
argued that the wrong global signals would be sent by a premature US
retreat.
Michael Littlejohns adds from New York: Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, the UN
secretary-general, will travel to Mogadishu next week to review military
operations. In advance of his trip, Mr Kofi Annan, head of UN peacekeeping
operations worldwide, is to visit the country to demonstrate 'solidarity
with the troops on the ground' and confer with force commanders.
</TEXT>
